<doc id="13717" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=13717" title="Australian Prime Minister's popularity at all time low">
<h1>Australian Prime Minister's popularity at all time low</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Australian%20Prime%20Minister%27s%20popularity%20at%20all%20time%20low&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

According to recent polls, Australian Prime Minister &lt;a href="w%3AJohn%20Howard"&gt;John Howard&lt;/a&gt;'s popularity has hit an all time low in response to his policies in industrial relations. This has combined with a backlash against Treasurer &lt;a href="w%3APeter%20Costello"&gt;w:Peter Costello&lt;/a&gt;, after he said in an interview on ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3ALateline%20%28news%29"&gt;Lateline&lt;/a&gt;♡❤ that religious teachings caused children "only a little harm". This comment followed a media stunt at a major church where Mr. Costello was attempting to capture the "Religious Right" vote.

The Liberal party has hit back by calling the public reaction "Labor propaganda". 

