<doc id="14389" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=14389" title="Walt Disney Co. reconciles with Disney heir">
<h1>Walt Disney Co. reconciles with Disney heir</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Walt%20Disney%20Co.%20reconciles%20with%20Disney%20heir&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 
Today &lt;a href="w%3AThe%20Walt%20Disney%20Company"&gt;The Walt Disney Company&lt;/a&gt; issued a joint statement with business partners &lt;a href="w%3ARoy%20E.%20Disney"&gt;Roy E. Disney&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="w%3AStanley%20Gold"&gt;Stanley Gold&lt;/a&gt; to the media, as a show of reunion between the two camps after nearly three years of hostility. 

Roy E. Disney, son of company co-founder &lt;a href="w%3ARoy%20O.%20Disney"&gt;Roy O. Disney&lt;/a&gt; and nephew of the company namesake &lt;a href="w%3AWalt%20Disney"&gt;Walt Disney&lt;/a&gt;, had resigned from his job as chairman of &lt;a href="w%3AWalt%20Disney%20Feature%20Animation"&gt;Feature Animation&lt;/a&gt; at the company after experiencing difficulty with the company's board of directors, many of whom were biased towards company CEO &lt;a href="w%3AMichael%20Eisner"&gt;Michael Eisner&lt;/a&gt;'s view of what direction the company should take. 

Eisner is due to retire from the company this September, and the talks with Disney and Gold are believed to have been led by Eisner's successor, &lt;a href="w%3ABob%20Iger"&gt;Bob Iger&lt;/a&gt;, who is currently President and COO of the company. Iger has shown great interest in building relationships back up with many companies who have refused to work with Disney until Eisner leaves, such as &lt;a href="w%3APixar"&gt;Pixar Animation&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="w%3AGeorge%20Lucas"&gt;George Lucas&lt;/a&gt;.

Large scores of Disney fans had hoped Roy would read the &lt;a href="w%3ADisneyland"&gt;Disneyland&lt;/a&gt; Dedication Speech on the theme park's fiftieth birthday next week, which was originally read by Walt on the park's opening day, but Roy had already entered an annual sailing race from &lt;a href="w%3ALos%20Angeles"&gt;Los Angeles&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href="w%3AHonolulu"&gt;Honolulu&lt;/a&gt;. 

<h2>Sources</h2>
<ul>
BULLET::::- The Walt Disney Company, Roy E. Disney and Stanley P. Gold. "&lt;a href="http%3A//www.savedisney.com/"&gt;Joint Statement from The Walt Disney Co. and Roy E. Disney and Stanley P. Gold&lt;/a&gt;" — &lt;i&gt;&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3ASaveDisney.org"&gt;SaveDisney.org&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/i&gt;, July 8, 2005

</ul>
<ul>
BULLET::::- Stephanie Saul. "&lt;a href="http%3A//www.nytimes.com/2005/07/09/business/media/09disney.html%3Fhp%26amp%3Bex%3D1120881600%26amp%3Ben%3Db2cb3676bec2f125%26amp%3Bei%3D5094%26amp%3Bpartner%3Dhomepage"&gt;Disney Mends Rift With Kin of Founder&lt;/a&gt;" — &lt;i&gt;&lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AThe%20New%20York%20Times"&gt;The New York Times&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/i&gt;, July 9, 2005

</ul>


