<doc id="14921" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=14921" title="Ft. Wayne, Indiana burn center treats Afghan child">
<h1>Ft. Wayne, Indiana burn center treats Afghan child</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Ft.%20Wayne%2C%20Indiana%20burn%20center%20treats%20Afghan%20child&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

Doctors at the regional burn center at St. Joseph Hospital in &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AFort%20Wayne%2C%20Indiana"&gt;Fort Wayne&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , &lt;a href="Indiana"&gt;Indiana&lt;/a&gt; are treating a patient flown in from war-torn &lt;a href="Afghanistan"&gt;Afghanistan&lt;/a&gt;. 

U.S. Army's 113th Battalion, which is made up of &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AIndiana%20National%20Guard"&gt;Indiana National Guardsman&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; , discovered five-year-old Zia after a propane explosion in suburban &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3AKabul"&gt;Kabul&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; earlier this year destroyed homes and killed six of the boy's family members. 

The blast left Zia with &lt;span class="interwiki-link-foreign"&gt;&lt;a href="w%3Athird%20degree%20burn"&gt;third degree burns&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; on his arms, torso and legs. Guardsmen, familiar with the Fort Wayne burn center, worked with non-profit group, Northeast Indiana Burn Council to raised $18,500 to fly Zia, accompanied by his father Abdul Qahir, to Fort Wayne for treatment.

Upon arrival, he was rushed to the St. Joseph burn unit, where after a few days of recovery from
travel, underwent his first surgery June 23. The second and final surgery was postponed nine
days from an original date of July 2 because the boy developed an infection in one of his wounds,
which is common for burn patients.

The second surgery grafted skin onto burn wounds on Zia's arm, chest and the second toe on his
right foot. Tuesday, doctors said Zia was recovering and appeared to be in good spirits. In
preparation for their planned return trip to Afghanistan in September, doctors are teaching Zia's
father physical therapy techniques needed for further recovery. "Without good therapy, he could
be right back where we started," Dr. John Mancoll, the lead surgeon on the case, said in an
interview with the ♡❤Fort Wayne Journal Gazette♡❤ newspaper.

